doc.after: The economy of California is large enough to be comparable to that of the largest of countries. As of 2013[update], the gross state product (GSP) is about $2.203 trillion, the largest in the United States.[124] California is responsible for 13.2 percent of the United States' approximate $16.7 trillion gross domestic product (GDP).[124] California's GDP is larger than that of all but 7 countries in dollar terms (the United States, China, Japan, Germany, France, Brazil, and the United Kingdom),[125][126] larger than Russia, Italy, India, Canada, Australia, and Spain. In Purchasing Power Parity,[127] it is larger than all but 10 countries (the United States, China, India, Japan, Germany, Russia, Brazil, France, the United Kingdom, and Indonesia), larger than Italy, Mexico, Spain, South Korea, Saudi Arabia, and Canada.[128]
